Reproductibility of Chosen R Journal Papers

Jakub SzypuÅ‚a

31/03/2020

Introduction

This report deals with reproductibility of three, chosen by the author, R Journal papers. In the paragraphs below, an attempt will be made to reproduce said papers.

Mapping and Measuring Country Shapes

An article written by Nils B. Weidmann and Kristian Skrede Gleditsch, published in 2010.

Link to the article

What is there to reproduce?

The article includes seven code chunks, however, only two are evaluated. The remaining five illustrate how one could implement certain tasks, using package provided by the authors (e.g.Â generating weights from a distance matrix). Therefore, reproducing these 5 code chunks is definitely possible, however, it is impossible to judge whether the code executes the way it was intended. The remaining two code chunks are dealt with below.

Evaluated Code chunk #1

In the article the following code chunk is used to generate a world map, where each countryâ€™s color corresponds to its regime type in 2002.

# download dataset, filter scores for 2002
polity.file <- paste(tempdir(), "p4v2008.sav", sep="/")
download.file("http://www.systemicpeace.org/inscr/p4v2008.sav", polity.file)
## Error in download.file("http://www.systemicpeace.org/inscr/p4v2008.sav", : cannot open URL 'http://www.systemicpeace.org/inscr/p4v2008.sav'

Unfortunately, the link above is dead. Consequently, the following code cannot be run, as it lacks the very data necessary to execute it.

Evaluated Code chunk #2

In this code chunk, a minimal distance matrix (i.e.Â a matrix where each element \(A_{i, j}\) is the distance between country \(i\) and \(j\)) is calculated twice, once using default tolerance parameter for the Douglas-Pecker polygon simplification algorithm and secondly using tolerance equal to 0 (no simplification).

system.time(dmat.simple <- distmatrix(as.Date("2002-1-1"), type="mindist"))
##    user  system elapsed 
##  134.25    0.50  137.25
system.time(dmat.full <- distmatrix(as.Date("2002-1-1"), type="mindist", tolerance = 0))
##    user  system elapsed 
## 6546.27  287.18 7646.58
# correlation between the two
cor(as.vector(dmat.simple),as.vector(dmat.full))
## [1] 0.9987394

This time, the chunk was reproducible. Time to process the chunk was approximately halved, compared to the original. Interestingly, the correlation between the two matrices was slightly lower (~0.016%), than in the article.

Summary

Out of 7 code chunks, 5 were not evaluated, one was evaluated and was reproduced successfully and one was evaluated, but it could not be reproduced. It was due to the fact, that the link to download the necessary data was expired.

stplanr: A Package for Transport Planning

An article by Robin Lovelace, Richard Ellison, published in 2018.

Link to the article

An .R file was attached to the article, which helped with reproductibility.

What is there to reproduce?

The article contains on evaluated code chunk and 8 figures, of which 7 were generated using R code.

Setup and Figure 1

if(!file.exists("reqfiles.RData"))
  download.file("https://github.com/Robinlovelace/stplanr/raw/rjournal-responses/lovelace/reqfiles.RData", "reqfiles.RData", mode = "wb")

One crucial change needed to be done - change of original buff_geo to geo_buffer, for the code to work. Since publication of the article, said function has been renamed.

Summary

Thanks to the attached .R file, reproducing this article has been relatively easy. There were minor mistakes, but attempt to reproduce the results directly from the article would have been futile, for most of strplanr functions used there have been either removed, moved to stats19 or renamed.

Furniture for Quantitative Scientists

An article by Tyson S. Barrett and Emily Brignone, published in 2017.

Link to the article

Curiously, this article mentions reproductibility itself. The authors imply that the furniture package could be used to provide sample summary statistics, simplifying the process of replicating the results.

What is there to reproduce?

The article contains 9 code chunks, 4 are evaluted and one produces a figure.

Summary

This article, despite not having an .R file included was also relatively easy to reproduce.

General Summary

Out of the three analysed articles, one could not be fully reproduced, one needed minor changes and one could be reproduced without issues (other than latex output in an HTML document, which is unrelated to the paper itself). I identified two major obstacles in the reproductibility of research papers, both related to the passage of time:

  • data necessary to reproduce the article no longer being available
  • functions used in the paper being either renamed, removed or moved to other packages
